        <name>22.2.1.6 Finding modal matrices</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For each of the following matrices, find a modal matrix \(P\):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(A={@matA@}\)&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;\( P=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(A={@matB@}\)&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;\( P=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
The eigenvalues of \(A={@matA@}\) are \({@eval1@}\) and \({@eval2@}\), with corresponding eigenvectors \({@evec1@}\) and \({@evec2@}\), respectively. Hence a modal matrix to \({@matA@}\) is \(P={@p1@}\). &lt;br&gt;We can confirm that 
&lt;br&gt;\(\qquad P^{-1}AP={@invert(p1)@}{@matA@}{@p1@}={@matD@},\)
&lt;br&gt;hence \({@p1@}\) is a modal matrix of \(A\).
&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt; For \(A={@matB@}\) we find eigenvalues \({@eval3@},{@eval4@}\), and \({@eval5@}\) with corresponding eigenvectors \({@evec3@},{@evec4@}\), and \({@evec5@}\). Hence a modal matrix is \(P={@p2@}\). &lt;br&gt;We can confirm that 
&lt;br&gt;\(\qquad P^{-1}AP={@invert(p2)@}{@matB@}{@p2@}={@matD2@},\)
&lt;br&gt;hence \({@p2@}\) is a modal matrix of \(A\).&lt;/li&gt;</generalfeedback>
